readme.md
    20‚Üí## Benefits over plain `fetch`
    21‚Üí
    22‚Üí- Simpler API
    23‚Üí- Method shortcuts (`ky.post()`)
    24‚Üí- Treats non-2xx status codes as errors (after redirects)
    25‚Üí- Retries failed requests
    26‚Üí- JSON option
    27‚Üí- Timeout support
    28‚Üí- URL prefix option
    29‚Üí- Instances with custom defaults
    30‚Üí- Hooks
    31‚Üí- TypeScript niceties (e.g. `.json()` supports generics and defaults to `unknown`, not `any`)
    32‚Üí
    33‚Üí## Install
    34‚Üí
    35‚Üí```sh
    36‚Üínpm install ky
    37‚Üí```
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí###### CDN
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí- [jsdelivr](https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ky/+esm)
    42‚Üí- [unpkg](https://unpkg.com/ky)
    43‚Üí- [esm.sh](https://esm.sh/ky)
    44‚Üí
    45‚Üí## Usage
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üí```js
    48‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üíconst json = await ky.post('https://example.com', {json: {foo: true}}).json();
    51‚Üí
    52‚Üíconsole.log(json);
    53‚Üí//=> {data: 'ü¶Ñ'}
    54‚Üí```
    55‚Üí
    56‚ÜíWith plain `fetch`, it would be:
    57‚Üí
    58‚Üí```js
    59‚Üíclass HTTPError extends Error {}
    60‚Üí
    61‚Üíconst response = await fetch('https://example.com', {
    62‚Üí	method: 'POST',
    63‚Üí	body: JSON.stringify({foo: true}),
    64‚Üí	headers: {
    65‚Üí		'content-type': 'application/json'
    66‚Üí	}
    67‚Üí});
    68‚Üí
    69‚Üíif (!response.ok) {
    70‚Üí	throw new HTTPError(`Fetch error: ${response.statusText}`);
    71‚Üí}
    72‚Üí
    73‚Üíconst json = await response.json();
    74‚Üí
    75‚Üíconsole.log(json);
    76‚Üí//=> {data: 'ü¶Ñ'}
    77‚Üí```
    78‚Üí
    79‚ÜíIf you are using [Deno](https://github.com/denoland/deno), import Ky from a URL. For example, using a CDN:
    80‚Üí
    81‚Üí```js
    82‚Üíimport ky from 'https://esm.sh/ky';
    83‚Üí```
    84‚Üí
    85‚Üí## API
    86‚Üí
    87‚Üí### ky(input, options?)
    88‚Üí
    89‚ÜíThe `input` and `options` are the same as [`fetch`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope/fetch), with additional `options` available (see below).
    90‚Üí
    91‚ÜíReturns a [`Response` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response) with [`Body` methods](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API/Using_Fetch#body) added for convenience. So you can, for example, call `ky.get(input).json()` directly without having to await the `Response` first. When called like that, an appropriate `Accept` header will be set depending on the body method used. Unlike the `Body` methods of `window.Fetch`, these will throw an `HTTPError` if the response status is not in the range of `200...299`. Also, `.json()` will return an empty string if body is empty or the response status is `204` instead of throwing a parse error due to an empty body.
    92‚Üí
    93‚ÜíAvailable body shortcuts: `.json()`, `.text()`, `.formData()`, `.arrayBuffer()`, `.blob()`, and `.bytes()`. The `.bytes()` shortcut is only present when the runtime supports `Response.prototype.bytes()`.
    94‚Üí
    95‚Üí```js
    96‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
    97‚Üí
    98‚Üíconst user = await ky('/api/user').json();
    99‚Üí
   100‚Üíconsole.log(user);
   101‚Üí```
   102‚Üí
   103‚Üí‚å®Ô∏è **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional [type parameter](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/generics.html), which defaults to [`unknown`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/functions.html#unknown), and is passed through to the return type of `.json()`.
   104‚Üí
   105‚Üí```ts
   106‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   107‚Üí
   108‚Üí// user1 is unknown
   109‚Üíconst user1 = await ky('/api/users/1').json();
   110‚Üí// user2 is a User
   111‚Üíconst user2 = await ky<User>('/api/users/2').json();
   112‚Üí// user3 is a User
   113‚Üíconst user3 = await ky('/api/users/3').json<User>();
   114‚Üí
   115‚Üíconsole.log([user1, user2, user3]);
   116‚Üí
   117‚Üí// Get raw bytes (when supported by the runtime)
   118‚Üíconst bytes = await ky('/api/file').bytes();
   119‚Üíconsole.log(bytes instanceof Uint8Array);
   120‚Üí```
   121‚Üí
   122‚Üí### ky.get(input, options?)
   123‚Üí### ky.post(input, options?)
   124‚Üí### ky.put(input, options?)
   125‚Üí### ky.patch(input, options?)
   126‚Üí### ky.head(input, options?)
   127‚Üí### ky.delete(input, options?)
   128‚Üí
   129‚ÜíSets `options.method` to the method name and makes a request.
   130‚Üí
   131‚Üí‚å®Ô∏è **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional type parameter for use with JSON responses (see [`ky()`](#kyinput-options)).
   132‚Üí
   133‚Üí#### input
   134‚Üí
   135‚ÜíType: `string` | `URL` | `Request`
   136‚Üí
   137‚ÜíSame as [`fetch` input](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request/Request#input).
   138‚Üí
   139‚ÜíWhen using a [`Request`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request) instance as `input`, any URL altering options (such as `prefixUrl`) will be ignored.
   140‚Üí
   141‚Üí#### options
   142‚Üí
   143‚ÜíType: `object`
   144‚Üí
   145‚ÜíSame as [`fetch` options](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/fetch#options), plus the following additional options:
   146‚Üí
   147‚Üí##### method
   148‚Üí
   149‚ÜíType: `string`\
   150‚ÜíDefault: `'get'`
   151‚Üí
   152‚ÜíHTTP method used to make the request.
   153‚Üí
   154‚ÜíInternally, the standard methods (`GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, `HEAD` and `DELETE`) are uppercased in order to avoid server errors due to case sensitivity.
   155‚Üí
   156‚Üí##### json
   157‚Üí
   158‚ÜíType: `object` and any other value accepted by [`JSON.stringify()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/JSON/stringify)
   159‚Üí
   160‚ÜíShortcut for sending JSON. Use this instead of the `body` option. Accepts any plain object or value, which will be `JSON.stringify()`'d and sent in the body with the correct header set.
   161‚Üí
   162‚Üí##### searchParams
   163‚Üí
   164‚ÜíType: `string | object<string, string | number | boolean | undefined> | Array<Array<string | number | boolean>> | URLSearchParams`\
   165‚ÜíDefault: `''`
   166‚Üí
   167‚ÜíSearch parameters to include in the request URL. Setting this will override all existing search parameters in the input URL.
   168‚Üí
   169‚ÜíAccepts any value supported by [`URLSearchParams()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/URLSearchParams/URLSearchParams).
   170‚Üí
   171‚ÜíWhen passing an object, `undefined` values are automatically filtered out, while `null` values are preserved and converted to the string `'null'`.
   172‚Üí
   173‚Üí##### prefixUrl
   174‚Üí
   175‚ÜíType: `string | URL`
   176‚Üí
   177‚ÜíA prefix to prepend to the `input` URL when making the request. It can be any valid URL, either relative or absolute. A trailing slash `/` is optional and will be added automatically, if needed, when it is joined with `input`. Only takes effect when `input` is a string. The `input` argument cannot start with a slash `/` when using this option.
   178‚Üí
   179‚ÜíUseful when used with [`ky.extend()`](#kyextenddefaultoptions) to create niche-specific Ky-instances.
   180‚Üí
   181‚Üí```js
   182‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   183‚Üí
   184‚Üí// On https://example.com
   185‚Üí
   186‚Üíconst response = await ky('unicorn', {prefixUrl: '/api'});
   187‚Üí//=> 'https://example.com/api/unicorn'
   188‚Üí
   189‚Üíconst response2 = await ky('unicorn', {prefixUrl: 'https://cats.com'});
   190‚Üí//=> 'https://cats.com/unicorn'
   191‚Üí```
   192‚Üí
   193‚ÜíNotes:
   194‚Üí - After `prefixUrl` and `input` are joined, the result is resolved against the [base URL](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Node/baseURI) of the page (if any).
   195‚Üí - Leading slashes in `input` are disallowed when using this option to enforce consistency and avoid confusion about how the `input` URL is handled, given that `input` will not follow the normal URL resolution rules when `prefixUrl` is being used, which changes the meaning of a leading slash.
   196‚Üí
   197‚Üí##### retry
   198‚Üí
   199‚ÜíType: `object | number`\
   200‚ÜíDefault:
   201‚Üí- `limit`: `2`
   202‚Üí- `methods`: `get` `put` `head` `delete` `options` `trace`
   203‚Üí- `statusCodes`: [`408`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/408) [`413`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/413) [`429`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/429) [`500`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/500) [`502`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/502) [`503`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/503) [`504`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/504)
   204‚Üí- `afterStatusCodes`: [`413`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/413), [`429`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/429), [`503`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/503)
   205‚Üí- `maxRetryAfter`: `undefined`
   206‚Üí- `backoffLimit`: `undefined`
   207‚Üí- `delay`: `attemptCount => 0.3 * (2 ** (attemptCount - 1)) * 1000`
   208‚Üí- `jitter`: `undefined`
   209‚Üí- `retryOnTimeout`: `false`
   210‚Üí- `shouldRetry`: `undefined`
   211‚Üí
   212‚ÜíAn object representing `limit`, `methods`, `statusCodes`, `afterStatusCodes`, `maxRetryAfter`, `backoffLimit`, `delay`, `jitter`, `retryOnTimeout`, and `shouldRetry` fields for maximum retry count, allowed methods, allowed status codes, status codes allowed to use the [`Retry-After`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Retry-After) time, maximum [`Retry-After`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Retry-After) time, backoff limit, delay calculation function, retry jitter, timeout retry behavior, and custom retry logic.
   213‚Üí
   214‚ÜíIf `retry` is a number, it will be used as `limit` and other defaults will remain in place.
   215‚Üí
   216‚ÜíIf the response provides an HTTP status contained in `afterStatusCodes`, Ky will wait until the date, timeout, or timestamp given in the [`Retry-After`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Retry-After) header has passed to retry the request. If `Retry-After` is missing, the non-standard [`RateLimit-Reset`](https://www.ietf.org/archive/id/draft-polli-ratelimit-headers-05.html#section-3.3) header is used in its place as a fallback. If the provided status code is not in the list, the [`Retry-After`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Retry-After) header will be ignored.
   217‚Üí
   218‚ÜíIf `maxRetryAfter` is set to `undefined`, it will use `options.timeout`. If [`Retry-After`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Retry-After) header is greater than `maxRetryAfter`, it will use `maxRetryAfter`.
   219‚Üí
   220‚ÜíThe `backoffLimit` option is the upper limit of the delay per retry in milliseconds.
   221‚ÜíTo clamp the delay, set `backoffLimit` to 1000, for example.
   222‚ÜíBy default, the delay is calculated with `0.3 * (2 ** (attemptCount - 1)) * 1000`. The delay increases exponentially.
   223‚Üí
   224‚ÜíThe `delay` option can be used to change how the delay between retries is calculated. The function receives one parameter, the attempt count, starting at `1`.
   225‚Üí
   226‚ÜíThe `jitter` option adds random jitter to retry delays to prevent thundering herd problems. When many clients retry simultaneously (e.g., after hitting a rate limit), they can overwhelm the server again. Jitter adds randomness to break this synchronization. Set to `true` to use full jitter, which randomizes the delay between 0 and the computed delay. Alternatively, pass a function to implement custom jitter strategies.
   227‚Üí
   228‚Üí**Note:** Jitter is not applied when the server provides a `Retry-After` header, as the server's explicit timing should be respected.
   229‚Üí
   230‚ÜíThe `retryOnTimeout` option determines whether to retry when a request times out. By default, retries are not triggered following a [timeout](#timeout).
   231‚Üí
   232‚ÜíThe `shouldRetry` option provides custom retry logic that **takes precedence over all other retry checks**. This function is called first, before any other retry validation.
   233‚Üí
   234‚Üí**Note:** This is different from the `beforeRetry` hook:
   235‚Üí- `shouldRetry`: Controls WHETHER to retry (called before the retry decision is made)
   236‚Üí- `beforeRetry`: Called AFTER retry is confirmed, allowing you to modify the request
   237‚Üí
   238‚ÜíThe function receives a state object with the error and retry count (starts at 1 for the first retry), and should return:
   239‚Üí- `true` to force a retry (bypasses `retryOnTimeout`, status code checks, and other validations)
   240‚Üí- `false` to prevent a retry (no retry will occur)
   241‚Üí- `undefined` to use the default retry logic (`retryOnTimeout`, status codes, etc.)
   242‚Üí
   243‚Üí**General example**
   244‚Üí
   245‚Üí```js
   246‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   247‚Üí
   248‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://example.com', {
   249‚Üí	retry: {
   250‚Üí		limit: 10,
   251‚Üí		methods: ['get'],
   252‚Üí		statusCodes: [413],
   253‚Üí		backoffLimit: 3000
   254‚Üí	}
   255‚Üí}).json();
   256‚Üí```
   257‚Üí
   258‚Üí**Retrying on timeout:**
   259‚Üí
   260‚Üí```js
   261‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   262‚Üí
   263‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://example.com', {
   264‚Üí	timeout: 5000,
   265‚Üí	retry: {
   266‚Üí		limit: 3,
   267‚Üí		retryOnTimeout: true
   268‚Üí	}
   269‚Üí}).json();
   270‚Üí```
   271‚Üí
   272‚Üí**Using jitter to prevent thundering herd:**
   273‚Üí
   274‚Üí```js
   275‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   276‚Üí
   277‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://example.com', {
   278‚Üí	retry: {
   279‚Üí		limit: 5,
   280‚Üí
   281‚Üí		// Full jitter (randomizes delay between 0 and computed value)
   282‚Üí		jitter: true
   283‚Üí
   284‚Üí		// Percentage jitter (80-120% of delay)
   285‚Üí		// jitter: delay => delay * (0.8 + Math.random() * 0.4)
   286‚Üí
   287‚Üí		// Absolute jitter (¬±100ms)
   288‚Üí		// jitter: delay => delay + (Math.random() * 200 - 100)
   289‚Üí	}
   290‚Üí}).json();
   291‚Üí```
   292‚Üí
   293‚Üí**Custom retry logic:**
   294‚Üí
   295‚Üí```js
   296‚Üíimport ky, {HTTPError} from 'ky';
   297‚Üí
   298‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://example.com', {
   299‚Üí	retry: {
   300‚Üí		limit: 3,
   301‚Üí		shouldRetry: ({error, retryCount}) => {
   302‚Üí			// Retry on specific business logic errors from API
   303‚Üí			if (error instanceof HTTPError) {
   304‚Üí				const status = error.response.status;
   305‚Üí
   306‚Üí				// Retry on 429 (rate limit) but only for first 2 attempts
   307‚Üí				if (status === 429 && retryCount <= 2) {
   308‚Üí					return true;
   309‚Üí				}
   310‚Üí
   311‚Üí				// Don't retry on 4xx errors except rate limits
   312‚Üí				if (status >= 400 && status < 500) {
   313‚Üí					return false;
   314‚Üí				}
   315‚Üí			}
   316‚Üí
   317‚Üí			// Use default retry logic for other errors
   318‚Üí			return undefined;
   319‚Üí		}
   320‚Üí	}
   321‚Üí}).json();
   322‚Üí```
   323‚Üí
   324‚Üí> [!NOTE]
   325‚Üí> Chromium-based browsers automatically retry `408 Request Timeout` responses at the network layer for keep-alive connections. This means requests may be retried by both the browser and ky. If you want to avoid duplicate retries, you can either set `keepalive: false` in your request options (though this may impact performance for multiple requests) or remove `408` from the retry status codes.
   326‚Üí
   327‚Üí##### timeout
   328‚Üí
   329‚ÜíType: `number | false`\
   330‚ÜíDefault: `10000`
   331‚Üí
   332‚ÜíTimeout in milliseconds for getting a response, including any retries. Can not be greater than 2147483647.
   333‚ÜíIf set to `false`, there will be no timeout.
   334‚Üí
   335‚Üí##### hooks
   336‚Üí
   337‚ÜíType: `object<string, Function[]>`\
   338‚ÜíDefault: `{beforeRequest: [], beforeRetry: [], afterResponse: []}`
   339‚Üí
   340‚ÜíHooks allow modifications during the request lifecycle. Hook functions may be async and are run serially.
   341‚Üí
   342‚Üí###### hooks.beforeRequest
   343‚Üí
   344‚ÜíType: `Function[]`\
   345‚ÜíDefault: `[]`
   346‚Üí
   347‚ÜíThis hook enables you to modify the request right before it is sent. Ky will make no further changes to the request after this. The hook function receives the normalized request, options, and a state object. You could, for example, modify the `request.headers` here.
   348‚Üí
   349‚ÜíThe `state.retryCount` is `0` for the initial request and increments with each retry. This allows you to distinguish between initial requests and retries, which is useful when you need different behavior for retries (e.g., avoiding overwriting headers set in `beforeRetry`).
   350‚Üí
   351‚ÜíThe hook can return a [`Request`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request) to replace the outgoing request, or return a [`Response`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response) to completely avoid making an HTTP request. This can be used to mock a request, check an internal cache, etc. An **important** consideration when returning a request or response from this hook is that any remaining `beforeRequest` hooks will be skipped, so you may want to only return them from the last hook.
   352‚Üí
   353‚Üí```js
   354‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   355‚Üí
   356‚Üíconst api = ky.extend({
   357‚Üí	hooks: {
   358‚Üí		beforeRequest: [
   359‚Üí			(request, options, {retryCount}) => {
   360‚Üí				// Only set default auth header on initial request, not on retries
   361‚Üí				// (retries may have refreshed token set by beforeRetry)
   362‚Üí				if (retryCount === 0) {
   363‚Üí					request.headers.set('Authorization', 'token initial-token');
   364‚Üí				}
   365‚Üí			}
   366‚Üí		]
   367‚Üí	}
   368‚Üí});
   369‚Üí
   370‚Üíconst response = await api.get('https://example.com/api/users');
   371‚Üí```
   372‚Üí
   373‚Üí###### hooks.beforeRetry
   374‚Üí
   375‚ÜíType: `Function[]`\
   376‚ÜíDefault: `[]`
   377‚Üí
   378‚ÜíThis hook enables you to modify the request right before retry. Ky will make no further changes to the request after this. The hook function receives an object with the normalized request and options, an error instance, and the retry count. You could, for example, modify `request.headers` here.
   379‚Üí
   380‚ÜíThe hook can return a [`Request`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request) to replace the outgoing retry request, or return a [`Response`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response) to skip the retry and use that response instead. **Note:** Returning a request or response skips remaining `beforeRetry` hooks.
   381‚Üí
   382‚ÜíThe `retryCount` is always `>= 1` since this hook is only called during retries, not on the initial request.
   383‚Üí
   384‚ÜíIf the request received a response, the error will be of type `HTTPError` and the `Response` object will be available at `error.response`. Be aware that some types of errors, such as network errors, inherently mean that a response was not received. In that case, the error will not be an instance of `HTTPError`.
   385‚Üí
   386‚ÜíYou can prevent Ky from retrying the request by throwing an error. Ky will not handle it in any way and the error will be propagated to the request initiator. The rest of the `beforeRetry` hooks will not be called in this case. Alternatively, you can return the [`ky.stop`](#kystop) symbol to do the same thing but without propagating an error (this has some limitations, see `ky.stop` docs for details).
   387‚Üí
   388‚Üí**Modifying headers:**
   389‚Üí
   390‚Üí```js
   391‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   392‚Üí
   393‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com', {
   394‚Üí	hooks: {
   395‚Üí		beforeRetry: [
   396‚Üí			async ({request, options, error, retryCount}) => {
   397‚Üí				const token = await ky('https://example.com/refresh-token');
   398‚Üí				request.headers.set('Authorization', `token ${token}`);
   399‚Üí			}
   400‚Üí		]
   401‚Üí	}
   402‚Üí});
   403‚Üí```
   404‚Üí
   405‚Üí**Modifying the request URL:**
   406‚Üí
   407‚Üí```js
   408‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   409‚Üí
   410‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com/api', {
   411‚Üí	hooks: {
   412‚Üí		beforeRetry: [
   413‚Üí			async ({request, error}) => {
   414‚Üí				// Add query parameters based on error response
   415‚Üí				if (error.response) {
   416‚Üí					const body = await error.response.json();
   417‚Üí					const url = new URL(request.url);
   418‚Üí					url.searchParams.set('processId', body.processId);
   419‚Üí					return new Request(url, request);
   420‚Üí				}
   421‚Üí			}
   422‚Üí		]
   423‚Üí	}
   424‚Üí});
   425‚Üí```
   426‚Üí
   427‚Üí**Returning a cached response:**
   428‚Üí
   429‚Üí```js
   430‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   431‚Üí
   432‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com/api', {
   433‚Üí	hooks: {
   434‚Üí		beforeRetry: [
   435‚Üí			({error, retryCount}) => {
   436‚Üí				// Use cached response instead of retrying
   437‚Üí				if (retryCount > 1 && cachedResponse) {
   438‚Üí					return cachedResponse;
   439‚Üí				}
   440‚Üí			}
   441‚Üí		]
   442‚Üí	}
   443‚Üí});
   444‚Üí```
   445‚Üí
   446‚Üí###### hooks.beforeError
   447‚Üí
   448‚ÜíType: `Function[]`\
   449‚ÜíDefault: `[]`
   450‚Üí
   451‚ÜíThis hook enables you to modify the `HTTPError` right before it is thrown. The hook function receives an `HTTPError` and a state object as arguments and should return an instance of `HTTPError`.
   452‚Üí
   453‚ÜíThe `state.retryCount` is `0` for the initial request and increments with each retry. This allows you to distinguish between the initial request and retries, which is useful when you need different error handling based on retry attempts (e.g., showing different error messages on the final attempt).
   454‚Üí
   455‚Üí```js
   456‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   457‚Üí
   458‚Üíawait ky('https://example.com', {
   459‚Üí	hooks: {
   460‚Üí		beforeError: [
   461‚Üí			async error => {
   462‚Üí				const {response} = error;
   463‚Üí				if (response) {
   464‚Üí					const body = await response.json();
   465‚Üí					error.name = 'GitHubError';
   466‚Üí					error.message = `${body.message} (${response.status})`;
   467‚Üí				}
   468‚Üí
   469‚Üí				return error;
   470‚Üí			},
   471‚Üí
   472‚Üí			// Or show different message based on retry count
   473‚Üí			(error, state) => {
   474‚Üí				if (state.retryCount === error.options.retry.limit) {
   475‚Üí					error.message = `${error.message} (failed after ${state.retryCount} retries)`;
   476‚Üí				}
   477‚Üí
   478‚Üí				return error;
   479‚Üí			}
   480‚Üí		]
   481‚Üí	}
   482‚Üí});
   483‚Üí```
   484‚Üí
   485‚Üí###### hooks.afterResponse
   486‚Üí
   487‚ÜíType: `Function[]`\
   488‚ÜíDefault: `[]`
   489‚Üí
   490‚ÜíThis hook enables you to read and optionally modify the response. The hook function receives normalized request, options, a clone of the response, and a state object. The return value of the hook function will be used by Ky as the response object if it's an instance of [`Response`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response).
   491‚Üí
   492‚ÜíYou can also force a retry by returning [`ky.retry(options)`](#kyretryoptions). This is useful when you need to retry based on the response body content, even if the response has a successful status code. The retry will respect the `retry.limit` option and be observable in `beforeRetry` hooks.
   493‚Üí
   494‚ÜíThe `state.retryCount` is `0` for the initial request and increments with each retry. This allows you to distinguish between initial requests and retries, which is useful when you need different behavior for retries (e.g., showing a notification only on the final retry).
   495‚Üí
   496‚Üí```js
   497‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   498‚Üí
   499‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com', {
   500‚Üí	hooks: {
   501‚Üí		afterResponse: [
   502‚Üí			(_request, _options, response) => {
   503‚Üí				// You could do something with the response, for example, logging.
   504‚Üí				log(response);
   505‚Üí
   506‚Üí				// Or return a `Response` instance to overwrite the response.
   507‚Üí				return new Response('A different response', {status: 200});
   508‚Üí			},
   509‚Üí
   510‚Üí			// Or retry with a fresh token on a 401 error
   511‚Üí			async (request, _options, response, state) => {
   512‚Üí				if (response.status === 401 && state.retryCount === 0) {
   513‚Üí					// Only refresh on first 401, not on subsequent retries
   514‚Üí					const {token} = await ky.post('https://example.com/auth/refresh').json();
   515‚Üí
   516‚Üí					const headers = new Headers(request.headers);
   517‚Üí					headers.set('Authorization', `Bearer ${token}`);
   518‚Üí
   519‚Üí					return ky.retry({
   520‚Üí						request: new Request(request, {headers}),
   521‚Üí						code: 'TOKEN_REFRESHED'
   522‚Üí					});
   523‚Üí				}
   524‚Üí			},
   525‚Üí
   526‚Üí			// Or force retry based on response body content
   527‚Üí			async (request, options, response) => {
   528‚Üí				if (response.status === 200) {
   529‚Üí					const data = await response.clone().json();
   530‚Üí					if (data.error?.code === 'RATE_LIMIT') {
   531‚Üí						// Retry with custom delay from API response
   532‚Üí						return ky.retry({
   533‚Üí							delay: data.error.retryAfter * 1000,
   534‚Üí							code: 'RATE_LIMIT'
   535‚Üí						});
   536‚Üí					}
   537‚Üí				}
   538‚Üí			},
   539‚Üí
   540‚Üí			// Or show a notification only on the last retry for 5xx errors
   541‚Üí			(request, options, response, {retryCount}) => {
   542‚Üí				if (response.status >= 500 && response.status <= 599) {
   543‚Üí					if (retryCount === options.retry.limit) {
   544‚Üí						showNotification('Request failed after all retries');
   545‚Üí					}
   546‚Üí				}
   547‚Üí			}
   548‚Üí		]
   549‚Üí	}
   550‚Üí});
   551‚Üí```
   552‚Üí
   553‚Üí##### throwHttpErrors
   554‚Üí
   555‚ÜíType: `boolean | (status: number) => boolean`\
   556‚ÜíDefault: `true`
   557‚Üí
   558‚ÜíThrow an `HTTPError` when, after following redirects, the response has a non-2xx status code. To also throw for redirects instead of following them, set the [`redirect`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope/fetch#Parameters) option to `'manual'`.
   559‚Üí
   560‚ÜíSetting this to `false` may be useful if you are checking for resource availability and are expecting error responses.
   561‚Üí
   562‚ÜíYou can also pass a function that accepts the HTTP status code and returns a boolean for selective error handling. Note that this can violate the principle of least surprise, so it's recommended to use the boolean form unless you have a specific use case like treating 404 responses differently.
   563‚Üí
   564‚ÜíNote: If `false`, error responses are considered successful and the request will not be retried.
   565‚Üí
   566‚Üí##### onDownloadProgress
   567‚Üí
   568‚ÜíType: `Function`
   569‚Üí
   570‚ÜíDownload progress event handler.
   571‚Üí
   572‚ÜíThe function receives these arguments:
   573‚Üí- `progress` is an object with the these properties:
   574‚Üí- - `percent` is a number between 0 and 1 representing the progress percentage.
   575‚Üí- - `transferredBytes` is the number of bytes transferred so far.
   576‚Üí- - `totalBytes` is the total number of bytes to be transferred. This is an estimate and may be 0 if the total size cannot be determined.
   577‚Üí- `chunk` is an instance of `Uint8Array` containing the data that was sent. Note: It's empty for the first call.
   578‚Üí
   579‚Üí```js
   580‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   581‚Üí
   582‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com', {
   583‚Üí	onDownloadProgress: (progress, chunk) => {
   584‚Üí		// Example output:
   585‚Üí		// `0% - 0 of 1271 bytes`
   586‚Üí		// `100% - 1271 of 1271 bytes`
   587‚Üí		console.log(`${progress.percent * 100}% - ${progress.transferredBytes} of ${progress.totalBytes} bytes`);
   588‚Üí	}
   589‚Üí});
   590‚Üí```
   591‚Üí
   592‚Üí##### onUploadProgress
   593‚Üí
   594‚ÜíType: `Function`
   595‚Üí
   596‚ÜíUpload progress event handler.
   597‚Üí
   598‚ÜíThe function receives these arguments:
   599‚Üí- `progress` is an object with the these properties:
   600‚Üí- - `percent` is a number between 0 and 1 representing the progress percentage.
   601‚Üí- - `transferredBytes` is the number of bytes transferred so far.
   602‚Üí- - `totalBytes` is the total number of bytes to be transferred. This is an estimate and may be 0 if the total size cannot be determined.
   603‚Üí- `chunk` is an instance of `Uint8Array` containing the data that was sent. Note: It's empty for the last call.
   604‚Üí
   605‚Üí```js
   606‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   607‚Üí
   608‚Üíconst response = await ky.post('https://example.com/upload', {
   609‚Üí	body: largeFile,
   610‚Üí	onUploadProgress: (progress, chunk) => {
   611‚Üí		// Example output:
   612‚Üí		// `0% - 0 of 1271 bytes`
   613‚Üí		// `100% - 1271 of 1271 bytes`
   614‚Üí		console.log(`${progress.percent * 100}% - ${progress.transferredBytes} of ${progress.totalBytes} bytes`);
   615‚Üí	}
   616‚Üí});
   617‚Üí```
   618‚Üí
   619‚Üí##### parseJson
   620‚Üí
   621‚ÜíType: `Function`\
   622‚ÜíDefault: `JSON.parse()`
   623‚Üí
   624‚ÜíUser-defined JSON-parsing function.
   625‚Üí
   626‚ÜíUse-cases:
   627‚Üí1. Parse JSON via the [`bourne` package](https://github.com/hapijs/bourne) to protect from prototype pollution.
   628‚Üí2. Parse JSON with [`reviver` option of `JSON.parse()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/JSON/parse).
   629‚Üí
   630‚Üí```js
   631‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   632‚Üíimport bourne from '@hapijs/bourne';
   633‚Üí
   634‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://example.com', {
   635‚Üí	parseJson: text => bourne(text)
   636‚Üí}).json();
   637‚Üí```
   638‚Üí
   639‚Üí##### stringifyJson
   640‚Üí
   641‚ÜíType: `Function`\
   642‚ÜíDefault: `JSON.stringify()`
   643‚Üí
   644‚ÜíUser-defined JSON-stringifying function.
   645‚Üí
   646‚ÜíUse-cases:
   647‚Üí1. Stringify JSON with a custom `replacer` function.
   648‚Üí
   649‚Üí```js
   650‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   651‚Üíimport {DateTime} from 'luxon';
   652‚Üí
   653‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://example.com', {
   654‚Üí	stringifyJson: data => JSON.stringify(data, (key, value) => {
   655‚Üí		if (key.endsWith('_at')) {
   656‚Üí			return DateTime.fromISO(value).toSeconds();
   657‚Üí		}
   658‚Üí
   659‚Üí		return value;
   660‚Üí	})
   661‚Üí}).json();
   662‚Üí```
   663‚Üí
   664‚Üí##### fetch
   665‚Üí
   666‚ÜíType: `Function`\
   667‚ÜíDefault: `fetch`
   668‚Üí
   669‚ÜíUser-defined `fetch` function.
   670‚ÜíHas to be fully compatible with the [Fetch API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API) standard.
   671‚Üí
   672‚ÜíUse-cases:
   673‚Üí1. Use custom `fetch` implementations like [`isomorphic-unfetch`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/isomorphic-unfetch).
   674‚Üí2. Use the `fetch` wrapper function provided by some frameworks that use server-side rendering (SSR).
   675‚Üí
   676‚Üí```js
   677‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   678‚Üíimport fetch from 'isomorphic-unfetch';
   679‚Üí
   680‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://example.com', {fetch}).json();
   681‚Üí```
   682‚Üí
   683‚Üí##### context
   684‚Üí
   685‚ÜíType: `object<string, unknown>`\
   686‚ÜíDefault: `{}`
   687‚Üí
   688‚ÜíUser-defined data passed to hooks.
   689‚Üí
   690‚ÜíThis option allows you to pass arbitrary contextual data to hooks without polluting the request itself. The context is available in all hooks and is **guaranteed to always be an object** (never `undefined`), so you can safely access properties without optional chaining.
   691‚Üí
   692‚ÜíUse cases:
   693‚Üí- Pass authentication tokens or API keys to hooks
   694‚Üí- Attach request metadata for logging or debugging
   695‚Üí- Implement conditional logic in hooks based on the request context
   696‚Üí- Pass serverless environment bindings (e.g., Cloudflare Workers)
   697‚Üí
   698‚Üí**Note:** Context is shallow merged. Top-level properties are merged, but nested objects are replaced. Only enumerable properties are copied.
   699‚Üí
   700‚Üí```js
   701‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   702‚Üí
   703‚Üí// Pass data to hooks
   704‚Üíconst api = ky.create({
   705‚Üí	hooks: {
   706‚Üí		beforeRequest: [
   707‚Üí			(request, options) => {
   708‚Üí				const {token} = options.context;
   709‚Üí				if (token) {
   710‚Üí					request.headers.set('Authorization', `Bearer ${token}`);
   711‚Üí				}
   712‚Üí			}
   713‚Üí		]
   714‚Üí	}
   715‚Üí});
   716‚Üí
   717‚Üíawait api('https://example.com', {
   718‚Üí	context: {
   719‚Üí		token: 'secret123'
   720‚Üí	}
   721‚Üí}).json();
   722‚Üí
   723‚Üí// Shallow merge: only top-level properties are merged
   724‚Üíconst instance = ky.create({
   725‚Üí	context: {
   726‚Üí		a: 1,
   727‚Üí		b: {
   728‚Üí			nested: true
   729‚Üí		}
   730‚Üí	}
   731‚Üí});
   732‚Üí
   733‚Üíconst extended = instance.extend({
   734‚Üí	context: {
   735‚Üí		b: {
   736‚Üí			updated: true
   737‚Üí		},
   738‚Üí		c: 3
   739‚Üí	}
   740‚Üí});
   741‚Üí// Result: {a: 1, b: {updated: true}, c: 3}
   742‚Üí// Note: The original `b.nested` is gone (shallow merge)
   743‚Üí```
   744‚Üí
   745‚Üí### ky.extend(defaultOptions)
   746‚Üí
   747‚ÜíCreate a new `ky` instance with some defaults overridden with your own.
   748‚Üí
   749‚ÜíIn contrast to `ky.create()`, `ky.extend()` inherits defaults from its parent.
   750‚Üí
   751‚ÜíYou can pass headers as a `Headers` instance or a plain object.
   752‚Üí
   753‚ÜíYou can remove a header with `.extend()` by passing the header with an `undefined` value.
   754‚ÜíPassing `undefined` as a string removes the header only if it comes from a `Headers` instance.
   755‚Üí
   756‚ÜíSimilarly, you can remove existing `hooks` entries by extending the hook with an explicit `undefined`.
   757‚Üí
   758‚Üí```js
   759‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   760‚Üí
   761‚Üíconst url = 'https://sindresorhus.com';
   762‚Üí
   763‚Üíconst original = ky.create({
   764‚Üí	headers: {
   765‚Üí		rainbow: 'rainbow',
   766‚Üí		unicorn: 'unicorn'
   767‚Üí	},
   768‚Üí	hooks: {
   769‚Üí		beforeRequest: [ () => console.log('before 1') ],
   770‚Üí		afterResponse: [ () => console.log('after 1') ],
   771‚Üí	},
   772‚Üí});
   773‚Üí
   774‚Üíconst extended = original.extend({
   775‚Üí	headers: {
   776‚Üí		rainbow: undefined
   777‚Üí	},
   778‚Üí	hooks: {
   779‚Üí		beforeRequest: undefined,
   780‚Üí		afterResponse: [ () => console.log('after 2') ],
   781‚Üí	}
   782‚Üí});
   783‚Üí
   784‚Üíconst response = await extended(url).json();
   785‚Üí//=> after 1
   786‚Üí//=> after 2
   787‚Üí
   788‚Üíconsole.log('rainbow' in response);
   789‚Üí//=> false
   790‚Üí
   791‚Üíconsole.log('unicorn' in response);
   792‚Üí//=> true
   793‚Üí```
   794‚Üí
   795‚ÜíYou can also refer to parent defaults by providing a function to `.extend()`.
   796‚Üí
   797‚Üí```js
   798‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   799‚Üí
   800‚Üíconst api = ky.create({prefixUrl: 'https://example.com/api'});
   801‚Üí
   802‚Üíconst usersApi = api.extend((options) => ({prefixUrl: `${options.prefixUrl}/users`}));
   803‚Üí
   804‚Üíconst response = await usersApi.get('123');
   805‚Üí//=> 'https://example.com/api/users/123'
   806‚Üí
   807‚Üíconst response = await api.get('version');
   808‚Üí//=> 'https://example.com/api/version'
   809‚Üí```
   810‚Üí
   811‚Üí### ky.create(defaultOptions)
   812‚Üí
   813‚ÜíCreate a new Ky instance with complete new defaults.
   814‚Üí
   815‚Üí```js
   816‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   817‚Üí
   818‚Üí// On https://my-site.com
   819‚Üí
   820‚Üíconst api = ky.create({prefixUrl: 'https://example.com/api'});
   821‚Üí
   822‚Üíconst response = await api.get('users/123');
   823‚Üí//=> 'https://example.com/api/users/123'
   824‚Üí
   825‚Üíconst response = await api.get('/status', {prefixUrl: ''});
   826‚Üí//=> 'https://my-site.com/status'
   827‚Üí```
   828‚Üí
   829‚Üí#### defaultOptions
   830‚Üí
   831‚ÜíType: `object`
   832‚Üí
   833‚Üí### ky.stop
   834‚Üí
   835‚ÜíA `Symbol` that can be returned by a `beforeRetry` hook to stop the retry. This will also short circuit the remaining `beforeRetry` hooks.
   836‚Üí
   837‚ÜíNote: Returning this symbol makes Ky abort and return with an `undefined` response. Be sure to check for a response before accessing any properties on it or use [optional chaining](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Optional_chaining). It is also incompatible with body methods, such as `.json()` or `.text()`, because there is no response to parse. In general, we recommend throwing an error instead of returning this symbol, as that will cause Ky to abort and then throw, which avoids these limitations.
   838‚Üí
   839‚ÜíA valid use-case for `ky.stop` is to prevent retries when making requests for side effects, where the returned data is not important. For example, logging client activity to the server.
   840‚Üí
   841‚Üí```js
   842‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
   843‚Üí
   844‚Üíconst options = {
   845‚Üí	hooks: {
   846‚Üí		beforeRetry: [
   847‚Üí			async ({request, options, error, retryCount}) => {
   848‚Üí				const shouldStopRetry = await ky('https://example.com/api');
   849‚Üí				if (shouldStopRetry) {
   850‚Üí					return ky.stop;
   851‚Üí				}
   852‚Üí			}
   853‚Üí		]
   854‚Üí	}
   855‚Üí};
   856‚Üí
   857‚Üí// Note that response will be `undefined` in case `ky.stop` is returned.
   858‚Üíconst response = await ky.post('https://example.com', options);
   859‚Üí
   860‚Üí// Using `.text()` or other body methods is not supported.
   861‚Üíconst text = await ky('https://example.com', options).text();
   862‚Üí```
   863‚Üí
   864‚Üí### ky.retry(options?)
   865‚Üí
   866‚ÜíForce a retry from an `afterResponse` hook.
   867‚Üí
   868‚ÜíThis allows you to retry a request based on the response content, even if the response has a successful status code. The retry will respect the `retry.limit` option and skip the `shouldRetry` check. The forced retry is observable in `beforeRetry` hooks, where the error will be a `ForceRetryError` with the error name `'ForceRetryError'`.
   869‚Üí
   870‚Üí#### options
   871‚Üí
   872‚ÜíType: `object`
   873‚Üí
   874‚Üí##### delay
   875‚Üí
   876‚ÜíType: `number`
   877‚Üí
   878‚ÜíCustom delay in milliseconds before retrying. If not provided, uses the default retry delay calculation based on `retry.delay` configuration.
   879‚Üí
   880‚Üí**Note:** Custom delays bypass jitter and `backoffLimit`. This is intentional, as custom delays often come from server responses (e.g., `Retry-After` headers) and should be respected exactly as specified.
   881‚Üí
   882‚Üí##### code
   883‚Üí
   884‚ÜíType: `string`
   885‚Üí
   886‚ÜíError code for the retry.
   887‚Üí
   888‚ÜíThis machine-readable identifier will be included in the error message passed to `beforeRetry` hooks, allowing you to distinguish between different types of forced retries.
   889‚Üí
   890‚Üí```js
   891‚Üíreturn ky.retry({code: 'RATE_LIMIT'});
   892‚Üí// Resulting error message: 'Forced retry: RATE_LIMIT'
   893‚Üí```
   894‚Üí
   895‚Üí##### cause
   896‚Üí
   897‚ÜíType: `Error`
   898‚Üí
   899‚ÜíOriginal error that caused the retry. This allows you to preserve the error chain when forcing a retry based on caught exceptions. The error will be set as the `cause` of the `ForceRetryError`, enabling proper error chain traversal.
   900‚Üí
   901‚Üí```js
   902‚Üítry {
   903‚Üí	const data = await response.clone().json();
   904‚Üí	validateBusinessLogic(data);
   905‚Üí} catch (error) {
   906‚Üí	return ky.retry({
   907‚Üí		code: 'VALIDATION_FAILED',
   908‚Üí		cause: error  // Preserves original error in chain
   909‚Üí	});
   910‚Üí}
   911‚Üí```
   912‚Üí
   913‚Üí##### request
   914‚Üí
   915‚ÜíType: `Request`
   916‚Üí
   917‚ÜíCustom request to use for the retry.
   918‚Üí
   919‚ÜíThis allows you to modify or completely replace the request during a forced retry. The custom request becomes the starting point for the retry - `beforeRetry` hooks can still further modify it if needed.
   920‚Üí
   921‚Üí**Note:** The custom request's `signal` will be replaced with Ky's managed signal to handle timeouts and user-provided abort signals correctly. If the original request body has been consumed, you must provide a new body or clone the request before consuming.
   922‚Üí
   923‚Üí#### Example
   924‚Üí
   925‚Üí```js
   926‚Üíimport ky, {isForceRetryError} from 'ky';
   927‚Üí
   928‚Üíconst api = ky.extend({
   929‚Üí	hooks: {
   930‚Üí		afterResponse: [
   931‚Üí			async (request, options, response) => {
   932‚Üí				// Retry based on response body content
   933‚Üí				if (response.status === 200) {
   934‚Üí					const data = await response.clone().json();
   935‚Üí
   936‚Üí					// Simple retry with default delay
   937‚Üí					if (data.error?.code === 'TEMPORARY_ERROR') {
   938‚Üí						return ky.retry();
   939‚Üí					}
   940‚Üí
   941‚Üí					// Retry with custom delay from API response
   942‚Üí					if (data.error?.code === 'RATE_LIMIT') {
   943‚Üí						return ky.retry({
   944‚Üí							delay: data.error.retryAfter * 1000,
   945‚Üí							code: 'RATE_LIMIT'
   946‚Üí						});
   947‚Üí					}
   948‚Üí
   949‚Üí					// Retry with a modified request (e.g., fallback endpoint)
   950‚Üí					if (data.error?.code === 'FALLBACK_TO_BACKUP') {
   951‚Üí						return ky.retry({
   952‚Üí							request: new Request('https://backup-api.com/endpoint', {
   953‚Üí								method: request.method,
   954‚Üí								headers: request.headers,
   955‚Üí							}),
   956‚Üí							code: 'BACKUP_ENDPOINT'
   957‚Üí						});
   958‚Üí					}
   959‚Üí
   960‚Üí					// Retry with refreshed authentication
   961‚Üí					if (data.error?.code === 'TOKEN_REFRESH' && data.newToken) {
   962‚Üí						return ky.retry({
   963‚Üí							request: new Request(request, {
   964‚Üí								headers: {
   965‚Üí									...Object.fromEntries(request.headers),
   966‚Üí									'Authorization': `Bearer ${data.newToken}`
   967‚Üí								}
   968‚Üí							}),
   969‚Üí							code: 'TOKEN_REFRESHED'
   970‚Üí						});
   971‚Üí					}
   972‚Üí
   973‚Üí					// Retry with cause to preserve error chain
   974‚Üí					try {
   975‚Üí						validateResponse(data);
   976‚Üí					} catch (error) {
   977‚Üí						return ky.retry({
   978‚Üí							code: 'VALIDATION_FAILED',
   979‚Üí							cause: error
   980‚Üí						});
   981‚Üí					}
   982‚Üí				}
   983‚Üí			}
   984‚Üí		],
   985‚Üí		beforeRetry: [
   986‚Üí			({error, retryCount}) => {
   987‚Üí				// Observable in beforeRetry hooks
   988‚Üí				if (isForceRetryError(error)) {
   989‚Üí					console.log(`Forced retry #${retryCount}: ${error.message}`);
   990‚Üí					// Example output: "Forced retry #1: Forced retry: RATE_LIMIT"
   991‚Üí				}
   992‚Üí			}
   993‚Üí		]
   994‚Üí	}
   995‚Üí});
   996‚Üí
   997‚Üíconst response = await api.get('https://example.com/api');
   998‚Üí```
   999‚Üí
  1000‚Üí### HTTPError
  1001‚Üí
  1002‚ÜíExposed for `instanceof` checks. The error has a `response` property with the [`Response` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response), `request` property with the [`Request` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request), and `options` property with normalized options (either passed to `ky` when creating an instance with `ky.create()` or directly when performing the request).
  1003‚Üí
  1004‚ÜíBe aware that some types of errors, such as network errors, inherently mean that a response was not received. In that case, the error will not be an instance of HTTPError and will not contain a `response` property.
  1005‚Üí
  1006‚Üí> [!IMPORTANT]
  1007‚Üí> When catching an `HTTPError`, you must consume or cancel the `error.response` body to prevent resource leaks (especially in Deno and Bun).
  1008‚Üí
  1009‚Üí```js
  1010‚Üíimport {isHTTPError} from 'ky';
  1011‚Üí
  1012‚Üítry {
  1013‚Üí	await ky('https://example.com').json();
  1014‚Üí} catch (error) {
  1015‚Üí	if (isHTTPError(error)) {
  1016‚Üí		// Option 1: Read the error response body
  1017‚Üí		const errorJson = await error.response.json();
  1018‚Üí
  1019‚Üí		// Option 2: Cancel the body if you don't need it
  1020‚Üí		// await error.response.body?.cancel();
  1021‚Üí	}
  1022‚Üí}
  1023‚Üí```
  1024‚Üí
  1025‚ÜíYou can also use the `beforeError` hook:
  1026‚Üí
  1027‚Üí```js
  1028‚Üíawait ky('https://example.com', {
  1029‚Üí	hooks: {
  1030‚Üí		beforeError: [
  1031‚Üí			async error => {
  1032‚Üí				const {response} = error;
  1033‚Üí				if (response) {
  1034‚Üí					error.message = `${error.message}: ${await response.text()}`;
  1035‚Üí				}
  1036‚Üí
  1037‚Üí				return error;
  1038‚Üí			}
  1039‚Üí		]
  1040‚Üí	}
  1041‚Üí});
  1042‚Üí```
  1043‚Üí
  1044‚Üí‚å®Ô∏è **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional [type parameter](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/generics.html), which defaults to [`unknown`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/functions.html#unknown), and is passed through to the return type of `error.response.json()`.
  1045‚Üí
  1046‚Üí### TimeoutError
  1047‚Üí
  1048‚ÜíThe error thrown when the request times out. It has a `request` property with the [`Request` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request).
  1049‚Üí
  1050‚Üí## Tips
  1051‚Üí
  1052‚Üí### Sending form data
  1053‚Üí
  1054‚ÜíSending form data in Ky is identical to `fetch`. Just pass a [`FormData`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/FormData) instance to the `body` option. The `Content-Type` header will be automatically set to `multipart/form-data`, overriding any existing `Content-Type` header.
  1055‚Üí
  1056‚Üí```js
  1057‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1058‚Üí
  1059‚Üí// `multipart/form-data`
  1060‚Üíconst formData = new FormData();
  1061‚ÜíformData.append('food', 'fries');
  1062‚ÜíformData.append('drink', 'icetea');
  1063‚Üí
  1064‚Üíconst response = await ky.post(url, {body: formData});
  1065‚Üí```
  1066‚Üí
  1067‚ÜíIf you want to send the data in `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` format, you will need to encode the data with [`URLSearchParams`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/URLSearchParams). Like `FormData`, this will override any existing `Content-Type` headers.
  1068‚Üí
  1069‚Üí```js
  1070‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1071‚Üí
  1072‚Üí// `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`
  1073‚Üíconst searchParams = new URLSearchParams();
  1074‚ÜísearchParams.set('food', 'fries');
  1075‚ÜísearchParams.set('drink', 'icetea');
  1076‚Üí
  1077‚Üíconst response = await ky.post(url, {body: searchParams});
  1078‚Üí```
  1079‚Üí
  1080‚Üí#### Modifying FormData in hooks
  1081‚Üí
  1082‚ÜíIf you need to modify FormData in a `beforeRequest` hook (for example, to transform field names), delete the `Content-Type` header before creating a new `Request`:
  1083‚Üí
  1084‚Üí```js
  1085‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1086‚Üí
  1087‚Üíconst response = await ky.post(url, {
  1088‚Üí	body: formData,
  1089‚Üí	hooks: {
  1090‚Üí		beforeRequest: [
  1091‚Üí			request => {
  1092‚Üí				const newFormData = new FormData();
  1093‚Üí
  1094‚Üí				// Modify FormData as needed
  1095‚Üí				for (const [key, value] of formData) {
  1096‚Üí					newFormData.set(key.toLowerCase(), value);
  1097‚Üí				}
  1098‚Üí
  1099‚Üí				// Delete `Content-Type` to let Request regenerate it with correct boundary
  1100‚Üí				request.headers.delete('content-type');
  1101‚Üí
  1102‚Üí				return new Request(request, {body: newFormData});
  1103‚Üí			}
  1104‚Üí		]
  1105‚Üí	}
  1106‚Üí});
  1107‚Üí```
  1108‚Üí
  1109‚Üí### Setting a custom `Content-Type`
  1110‚Üí
  1111‚ÜíKy automatically sets an appropriate [`Content-Type`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Type) header for each request based on the data in the request body. However, some APIs require custom, non-standard content types, such as `application/x-amz-json-1.1`. Using the `headers` option, you can manually override the content type.
  1112‚Üí
  1113‚Üí```js
  1114‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1115‚Üí
  1116‚Üíconst json = await ky.post('https://example.com', {
  1117‚Üí	headers: {
  1118‚Üí		'content-type': 'application/json'
  1119‚Üí	},
  1120‚Üí	json: {
  1121‚Üí		foo: true
  1122‚Üí	},
  1123‚Üí}).json();
  1124‚Üí
  1125‚Üíconsole.log(json);
  1126‚Üí//=> {data: 'ü¶Ñ'}
  1127‚Üí```
  1128‚Üí
  1129‚Üí### Cancellation
  1130‚Üí
  1131‚ÜíFetch (and hence Ky) has built-in support for request cancellation through the [`AbortController` API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/AbortController). [Read more.](https://developers.google.com/web/updates/2017/09/abortable-fetch)
  1132‚Üí
  1133‚ÜíExample:
  1134‚Üí
  1135‚Üí```js
  1136‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1137‚Üí
  1138‚Üíconst controller = new AbortController();
  1139‚Üíconst {signal} = controller;
  1140‚Üí
  1141‚ÜísetTimeout(() => {
  1142‚Üí	controller.abort();
  1143‚Üí}, 5000);
  1144‚Üí
  1145‚Üítry {
  1146‚Üí	console.log(await ky(url, {signal}).text());
  1147‚Üí} catch (error) {
  1148‚Üí	if (error.name === 'AbortError') {
  1149‚Üí		console.log('Fetch aborted');
  1150‚Üí	} else {
  1151‚Üí		console.error('Fetch error:', error);
  1152‚Üí	}
  1153‚Üí}
  1154‚Üí```
  1155‚Üí
  1156‚Üí### Proxy support (Node.js)
  1157‚Üí
  1158‚Üí#### Native proxy support
  1159‚Üí
  1160‚ÜíNode.js 24.5+ supports automatic proxy configuration via environment variables. Set `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1` or use the `--use-env-proxy` CLI flag.
  1161‚Üí
  1162‚Üí```sh
  1163‚ÜíNODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1 HTTP_PROXY=http://proxy.example.com:8080 node app.js
  1164‚Üí```
  1165‚Üí
  1166‚ÜíOr:
  1167‚Üí
  1168‚Üí```sh
  1169‚Üínode --use-env-proxy app.js
  1170‚Üí```
  1171‚Üí
  1172‚ÜíSupported environment variables:
  1173‚Üí- `HTTP_PROXY` / `http_proxy`: Proxy URL for HTTP requests
  1174‚Üí- `HTTPS_PROXY` / `https_proxy`: Proxy URL for HTTPS requests
  1175‚Üí- `NO_PROXY` / `no_proxy`: Comma-separated list of hosts to bypass the proxy
  1176‚Üí
  1177‚Üí#### Using ProxyAgent
  1178‚Üí
  1179‚ÜíFor more control, use `ProxyAgent` or `EnvHttpProxyAgent` with the `dispatcher` option.
  1180‚Üí
  1181‚Üí```js
  1182‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1183‚Üíimport {ProxyAgent} from 'undici';
  1184‚Üí
  1185‚Üíconst proxyAgent = new ProxyAgent('http://proxy.example.com:8080');
  1186‚Üí
  1187‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com', {
  1188‚Üí	// @ts-expect-error - dispatcher is not in the type definition, but it's passed through to fetch.
  1189‚Üí	dispatcher: proxyAgent
  1190‚Üí}).json();
  1191‚Üí```
  1192‚Üí
  1193‚ÜíUsing `EnvHttpProxyAgent` to automatically read proxy settings from environment variables:
  1194‚Üí
  1195‚Üí```js
  1196‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1197‚Üíimport {EnvHttpProxyAgent} from 'undici';
  1198‚Üí
  1199‚Üíconst proxyAgent = new EnvHttpProxyAgent();
  1200‚Üí
  1201‚Üíconst api = ky.extend({
  1202‚Üí	// @ts-expect-error - dispatcher is not in the type definition, but it's passed through to fetch.
  1203‚Üí	dispatcher: proxyAgent
  1204‚Üí});
  1205‚Üí
  1206‚Üíconst response = await api('https://example.com').json();
  1207‚Üí```
  1208‚Üí
  1209‚Üí### HTTP/2 support (Node.js)
  1210‚Üí
  1211‚ÜíUndici supports HTTP/2, but it's not enabled by default. Create a custom dispatcher with the `allowH2` option:
  1212‚Üí
  1213‚Üí```js
  1214‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1215‚Üíimport {Agent, Pool} from 'undici';
  1216‚Üí
  1217‚Üíconst agent = new Agent({
  1218‚Üí	factory(origin, options) {
  1219‚Üí		return new Pool(origin, {
  1220‚Üí			...options,
  1221‚Üí			allowH2: true
  1222‚Üí		});
  1223‚Üí	}
  1224‚Üí});
  1225‚Üí
  1226‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com', {
  1227‚Üí	// @ts-expect-error - dispatcher is not in the type definition, but it's passed through to fetch.
  1228‚Üí	dispatcher: agent
  1229‚Üí}).json();
  1230‚Üí```
  1231‚Üí
  1232‚ÜíCombine proxy and HTTP/2:
  1233‚Üí
  1234‚Üí```js
  1235‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1236‚Üíimport {ProxyAgent} from 'undici';
  1237‚Üí
  1238‚Üíconst proxyAgent = new ProxyAgent({
  1239‚Üí	uri: 'http://proxy.example.com:8080',
  1240‚Üí	allowH2: true
  1241‚Üí});
  1242‚Üí
  1243‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://example.com', {
  1244‚Üí	// @ts-expect-error - dispatcher is not in the type definition, but it's passed through to fetch.
  1245‚Üí	dispatcher: proxyAgent
  1246‚Üí}).json();
  1247‚Üí```
  1248‚Üí
  1249‚Üí### Consuming Server-Sent Events (SSE)
  1250‚Üí
  1251‚ÜíUse [`parse-sse`](https://github.com/sindresorhus/parse-sse):
  1252‚Üí
  1253‚Üí```js
  1254‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1255‚Üíimport {parseServerSentEvents} from 'parse-sse';
  1256‚Üí
  1257‚Üíconst response = await ky('https://api.example.com/events');
  1258‚Üí
  1259‚Üífor await (const event of parseServerSentEvents(response)) {
  1260‚Üí	console.log(event.data);
  1261‚Üí}
  1262‚Üí```
  1263‚Üí
  1264‚Üí### Extending types
  1265‚Üí
  1266‚ÜíKy's TypeScript types are intentionally defined as type aliases rather than interfaces to prevent global module augmentation, which can lead to type conflicts and unexpected behavior across your codebase. If you need to add custom properties to Ky's types like `KyResponse` or `HTTPError`, create local wrapper types instead:
  1267‚Üí
  1268‚Üí```ts
  1269‚Üíimport ky, {HTTPError} from 'ky';
  1270‚Üí
  1271‚Üíinterface CustomError extends HTTPError {
  1272‚Üí	customProperty: unknown;
  1273‚Üí}
  1274‚Üí
  1275‚Üíconst api = ky.extend({
  1276‚Üí	hooks: {
  1277‚Üí		beforeError: [
  1278‚Üí			async error => {
  1279‚Üí				(error as CustomError).customProperty = 'value';
  1280‚Üí				return error;
  1281‚Üí			}
  1282‚Üí		]
  1283‚Üí	}
  1284‚Üí});
  1285‚Üí
  1286‚Üí// Use with type assertion
  1287‚Üíconst data = (error as CustomError).customProperty;
  1288‚Üí```
  1289‚Üí
  1290‚ÜíThis approach keeps your types scoped to where they're needed without polluting the global namespace.
  1291‚Üí
  1292‚Üí## FAQ
  1293‚Üí
  1294‚Üí#### How do I use this in Node.js?
  1295‚Üí
  1296‚ÜíNode.js 18 and later supports `fetch` natively, so you can just use this package directly.
  1297‚Üí
  1298‚Üí#### How do I use this with a web app (React, Vue.js, etc.) that uses server-side rendering (SSR)?
  1299‚Üí
  1300‚ÜíSame as above.
  1301‚Üí
  1302‚Üí#### How do I test a browser library that uses this?
  1303‚Üí
  1304‚ÜíEither use a test runner that can run in the browser, like Mocha, or use [AVA](https://avajs.dev) with `ky-universal`. [Read more.](https://github.com/sindresorhus/ky-universal#faq)
  1305‚Üí
  1306‚Üí#### How do I use this without a bundler like Webpack?
  1307‚Üí
  1308‚ÜíMake sure your code is running as a JavaScript module (ESM), for example by using a `<script type="module">` tag in your HTML document. Then Ky can be imported directly by that module without a bundler or other tools.
  1309‚Üí
  1310‚Üí```html
  1311‚Üí<script type="module">
  1312‚Üíimport ky from 'https://unpkg.com/ky/distribution/index.js';
  1313‚Üí
  1314‚Üíconst json = await ky('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1').json();
  1315‚Üí
  1316‚Üíconsole.log(json.title);
  1317‚Üí//=> 'delectus aut autem'
  1318‚Üí</script>
  1319‚Üí```
  1320‚Üí
  1321‚Üí#### How is it different from [`got`](https://github.com/sindresorhus/got)
  1322‚Üí
  1323‚ÜíGot is maintained by the same people as Ky, so you probably want Ky instead. It's smaller, works in the browser too, and is more stable since it's built on Fetch.
  1324‚Üí
  1325‚Üí#### How is it different from [`axios`](https://github.com/axios/axios)?
  1326‚Üí
  1327‚ÜíSee my answer [here](https://twitter.com/sindresorhus/status/1037763588826398720).
  1328‚Üí
  1329‚Üí#### How is it different from [`r2`](https://github.com/mikeal/r2)?
  1330‚Üí
  1331‚ÜíSee my answer in [#10](https://github.com/sindresorhus/ky/issues/10).
  1332‚Üí
  1333‚Üí#### What does `ky` mean?
  1334‚Üí
  1335‚ÜíIt's just a random short npm package name I managed to get. It does, however, have a meaning in Japanese:
  1336‚Üí
  1337‚Üí> A form of text-able slang, KY is an abbreviation for Á©∫Ê∞óË™≠„ÇÅ„Å™„ÅÑ (kuuki yomenai), which literally translates into ‚Äúcannot read the air.‚Äù It's a phrase applied to someone who misses the implied meaning.
  1338‚Üí
  1339‚Üí## Browser support
  1340‚Üí
  1341‚ÜíThe latest version of Chrome, Firefox, and Safari.
  1342‚Üí
  1343‚Üí## Node.js support
  1344‚Üí
  1345‚ÜíNode.js 18 and later.
  1346‚Üí
  1347‚Üí## Related
  1348‚Üí
  1349‚Üí- [fetch-extras](https://github.com/sindresorhus/fetch-extras) - Useful utilities for working with Fetch
  1350‚Üí- [ky-hooks-change-case](https://github.com/alice-health/ky-hooks-change-case) - Ky hooks to modify cases on requests and responses of objects
  1351‚Üí
  1352‚Üí## Maintainers
  1353‚Üí
  1354‚Üí- [Sindre Sorhus](https://github.com/sindresorhus)
  1355‚Üí- [Seth Holladay](https://github.com/sholladay)
  1356‚Üí- [Szymon Marczak](https://github.com/szmarczak)
source/core/Ky.ts
    33‚Üíexport class Ky {
    34‚Üí	static create(input: Input, options: Options): ResponsePromise {
    35‚Üí		const ky = new Ky(input, options);
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí		const function_ = async (): Promise<Response> => {
    38‚Üí			if (typeof ky.#options.timeout === 'number' && ky.#options.timeout > maxSafeTimeout) {
    39‚Üí				throw new RangeError(`The \`timeout\` option cannot be greater than ${maxSafeTimeout}`);
    40‚Üí			}
    41‚Üí
    42‚Üí			// Delay the fetch so that body method shortcuts can set the Accept header
    43‚Üí			await Promise.resolve();
    44‚Üí			// Before using ky.request, _fetch clones it and saves the clone for future retries to use.
    45‚Üí			// If retry is not needed, close the cloned request's ReadableStream for memory safety.
    46‚Üí			let response = await ky.#fetch();
    47‚Üí
    48‚Üí			for (const hook of ky.#options.hooks.afterResponse) {
    49‚Üí				// Clone the response before passing to hook so we can cancel it if needed
    50‚Üí				const clonedResponse = ky.#decorateResponse(response.clone());
    51‚Üí
    52‚Üí				let modifiedResponse;
    53‚Üí				try {
    54‚Üí					// eslint-disable-next-line no-await-in-loop
    55‚Üí					modifiedResponse = await hook(
    56‚Üí						ky.request,
    57‚Üí						ky.#getNormalizedOptions(),
    58‚Üí						clonedResponse,
    59‚Üí						{retryCount: ky.#retryCount},
    60‚Üí					);
    61‚Üí				} catch (error) {
    62‚Üí					// Cancel both responses to prevent memory leaks when hook throws
    63‚Üí					ky.#cancelResponseBody(clonedResponse);
    64‚Üí					ky.#cancelResponseBody(response);
    65‚Üí					throw error;
    66‚Üí				}
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí				if (modifiedResponse instanceof RetryMarker) {
    69‚Üí					// Cancel both the cloned response passed to the hook and the current response to prevent resource leaks (especially important in Deno/Bun).
    70‚Üí					// Do not await cancellation since hooks can clone the response, leaving extra tee branches that keep cancel promises pending per the Streams spec.
    71‚Üí					ky.#cancelResponseBody(clonedResponse);
    72‚Üí					ky.#cancelResponseBody(response);
    73‚Üí					throw new ForceRetryError(modifiedResponse.options);
    74‚Üí				}
    75‚Üí
    76‚Üí				// Determine which response to use going forward
    77‚Üí				const nextResponse = modifiedResponse instanceof globalThis.Response ? modifiedResponse : response;
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí				// Cancel any response bodies we won't use to prevent memory leaks.
    80‚Üí				// Uses fire-and-forget since hooks may have cloned the response, creating tee branches that block cancellation.
    81‚Üí				if (clonedResponse !== nextResponse) {
    82‚Üí					ky.#cancelResponseBody(clonedResponse);
    83‚Üí				}
    84‚Üí
    85‚Üí				if (response !== nextResponse) {
    86‚Üí					ky.#cancelResponseBody(response);
    87‚Üí				}
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí				response = nextResponse;
    90‚Üí			}
    91‚Üí
    92‚Üí			ky.#decorateResponse(response);
    93‚Üí
    94‚Üí			if (!response.ok && (
    95‚Üí				typeof ky.#options.throwHttpErrors === 'function'
    96‚Üí					? ky.#options.throwHttpErrors(response.status)
    97‚Üí					: ky.#options.throwHttpErrors
    98‚Üí			)) {
    99‚Üí				let error = new HTTPError(response, ky.request, ky.#getNormalizedOptions());
   100‚Üí
   101‚Üí				for (const hook of ky.#options.hooks.beforeError) {
   102‚Üí					// eslint-disable-next-line no-await-in-loop
   103‚Üí					error = await hook(error, {retryCount: ky.#retryCount});
   104‚Üí				}
   105‚Üí
   106‚Üí				throw error;
   107‚Üí			}
   108‚Üí
   109‚Üí			// If `onDownloadProgress` is passed, it uses the stream API internally
   110‚Üí			if (ky.#options.onDownloadProgress) {
   111‚Üí				if (typeof ky.#options.onDownloadProgress !== 'function') {
   112‚Üí					throw new TypeError('The `onDownloadProgress` option must be a function');
   113‚Üí				}
   114‚Üí
   115‚Üí				if (!supportsResponseStreams) {
   116‚Üí					throw new Error('Streams are not supported in your environment. `ReadableStream` is missing.');
   117‚Üí				}
   118‚Üí
   119‚Üí				const progressResponse = response.clone();
   120‚Üí				ky.#cancelResponseBody(response);
   121‚Üí				return streamResponse(progressResponse, ky.#options.onDownloadProgress);
   122‚Üí			}
   123‚Üí
   124‚Üí			return response;
   125‚Üí		};
   126‚Üí
   127‚Üí		// Always wrap in #retry to catch forced retries from afterResponse hooks
   128‚Üí		// Method retriability is checked in #calculateRetryDelay for non-forced retries
   129‚Üí		const result = ky.#retry(function_)
   130‚Üí			.finally(() => {
   131‚Üí				const originalRequest = ky.#originalRequest;
   132‚Üí
   133‚Üí				// Ignore cancellation errors from already-locked or already-consumed streams.
   134‚Üí				ky.#cancelBody(originalRequest?.body ?? undefined);
   135‚Üí				ky.#cancelBody(ky.request.body ?? undefined);
   136‚Üí			}) as ResponsePromise;
   137‚Üí
   138‚Üí		for (const [type, mimeType] of Object.entries(responseTypes) as ObjectEntries<typeof responseTypes>) {
   139‚Üí			// Only expose `.bytes()` when the environment implements it.
   140‚Üí			if (
   141‚Üí				type === 'bytes'
   142‚Üí				&& typeof (globalThis.Response?.prototype as unknown as {bytes?: unknown})?.bytes !== 'function'
   143‚Üí			) {
   144‚Üí				continue;
   145‚Üí			}
   146‚Üí
   147‚Üí			result[type] = async () => {
   148‚Üí				// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/prefer-nullish-coalescing
   149‚Üí				ky.request.headers.set('accept', ky.request.headers.get('accept') || mimeType);
   150‚Üí
   151‚Üí				const response = await result;
   152‚Üí
   153‚Üí				if (type === 'json') {
   154‚Üí					if (response.status === 204) {
   155‚Üí						return '';
   156‚Üí					}
   157‚Üí
   158‚Üí					const text = await response.text();
   159‚Üí					if (text === '') {
   160‚Üí						return '';
   161‚Üí					}
   162‚Üí
   163‚Üí					if (options.parseJson) {
   164‚Üí						return options.parseJson(text);
   165‚Üí					}
   166‚Üí
   167‚Üí					return JSON.parse(text);
   168‚Üí				}
   169‚Üí
   170‚Üí				return response[type]();
   171‚Üí			};
   172‚Üí		}
   173‚Üí
   174‚Üí		return result;
   175‚Üí	}
   176‚Üí
   177‚Üí	// eslint-disable-next-line unicorn/prevent-abbreviations
   178‚Üí	static #normalizeSearchParams(searchParams: SearchParamsOption): SearchParamsOption {
   179‚Üí		// Filter out undefined values from plain objects
   180‚Üí		if (searchParams && typeof searchParams === 'object' && !Array.isArray(searchParams) && !(searchParams instanceof URLSearchParams)) {
   181‚Üí			return Object.fromEntries(
   182‚Üí				Object.entries(searchParams).filter(([, value]) => value !== undefined),
   183‚Üí			);
   184‚Üí		}
   185‚Üí
   186‚Üí		return searchParams;
   187‚Üí	}
   188‚Üí
   189‚Üí	public request: Request;
   190‚Üí	#abortController?: AbortController;
   191‚Üí	#retryCount = 0;
   192‚Üí	// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/prefer-readonly -- False positive: #input is reassigned on line 202
   193‚Üí	#input: Input;
   194‚Üí	readonly #options: InternalOptions;
   195‚Üí	#originalRequest?: Request;
   196‚Üí	readonly #userProvidedAbortSignal?: AbortSignal;
   197‚Üí	#cachedNormalizedOptions: NormalizedOptions | undefined;
   198‚Üí
   199‚Üí	// eslint-disable-next-line complexity
   200‚Üí	constructor(input: Input, options: Options = {}) {
   201‚Üí		this.#input = input;
   202‚Üí
   203‚Üí		this.#options = {
   204‚Üí			...options,
   205‚Üí			headers: mergeHeaders((this.#input as Request).headers, options.headers),
   206‚Üí			hooks: mergeHooks(
   207‚Üí				{
   208‚Üí					beforeRequest: [],
   209‚Üí					beforeRetry: [],
   210‚Üí					beforeError: [],
   211‚Üí					afterResponse: [],
   212‚Üí				},
   213‚Üí				options.hooks,
   214‚Üí			),
   215‚Üí			method: normalizeRequestMethod(options.method ?? (this.#input as Request).method ?? 'GET'),
   216‚Üí			// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/prefer-nullish-coalescing
   217‚Üí			prefixUrl: String(options.prefixUrl || ''),
   218‚Üí			retry: normalizeRetryOptions(options.retry),
   219‚Üí			throwHttpErrors: options.throwHttpErrors ?? true,
   220‚Üí			timeout: options.timeout ?? 10_000,
   221‚Üí			fetch: options.fetch ?? globalThis.fetch.bind(globalThis),
   222‚Üí			context: options.context ?? {},
   223‚Üí		};
   224‚Üí
   225‚Üí		if (typeof this.#input !== 'string' && !(this.#input instanceof URL || this.#input instanceof globalThis.Request)) {
   226‚Üí			throw new TypeError('`input` must be a string, URL, or Request');
   227‚Üí		}
   228‚Üí
   229‚Üí		if (this.#options.prefixUrl && typeof this.#input === 'string') {
   230‚Üí			if (this.#input.startsWith('/')) {
   231‚Üí				throw new Error('`input` must not begin with a slash when using `prefixUrl`');
   232‚Üí			}
   233‚Üí
   234‚Üí			if (!this.#options.prefixUrl.endsWith('/')) {
   235‚Üí				this.#options.prefixUrl += '/';
   236‚Üí			}
   237‚Üí
   238‚Üí			this.#input = this.#options.prefixUrl + this.#input;
   239‚Üí		}
   240‚Üí
   241‚Üí		if (supportsAbortController && supportsAbortSignal) {
   242‚Üí			this.#userProvidedAbortSignal = this.#options.signal ?? (this.#input as Request).signal;
   243‚Üí			this.#abortController = new globalThis.AbortController();
   244‚Üí			this.#options.signal = this.#userProvidedAbortSignal ? AbortSignal.any([this.#userProvidedAbortSignal, this.#abortController.signal]) : this.#abortController.signal;
   245‚Üí		}
   246‚Üí
   247‚Üí		if (supportsRequestStreams) {
   248‚Üí			// @ts-expect-error - Types are outdated.
   249‚Üí			this.#options.duplex = 'half';
   250‚Üí		}
   251‚Üí
   252‚Üí		if (this.#options.json !== undefined) {
   253‚Üí			this.#options.body = this.#options.stringifyJson?.(this.#options.json) ?? JSON.stringify(this.#options.json);
   254‚Üí			this.#options.headers.set('content-type', this.#options.headers.get('content-type') ?? 'application/json');
   255‚Üí		}
   256‚Üí
   257‚Üí		// To provide correct form boundary, Content-Type header should be deleted when creating Request from another Request with FormData/URLSearchParams body
   258‚Üí		// Only delete if user didn't explicitly provide a custom content-type
   259‚Üí		const userProvidedContentType = options.headers && new globalThis.Headers(options.headers as HeadersInit).has('content-type');
   260‚Üí		if (
   261‚Üí			this.#input instanceof globalThis.Request
   262‚Üí			&& ((supportsFormData && this.#options.body instanceof globalThis.FormData) || this.#options.body instanceof URLSearchParams)
   263‚Üí			&& !userProvidedContentType
   264‚Üí		) {
   265‚Üí			this.#options.headers.delete('content-type');
   266‚Üí		}
   267‚Üí
   268‚Üí		this.request = new globalThis.Request(this.#input, this.#options);
   269‚Üí
   270‚Üí		if (hasSearchParameters(this.#options.searchParams)) {
   271‚Üí			// eslint-disable-next-line unicorn/prevent-abbreviations
   272‚Üí			const textSearchParams = typeof this.#options.searchParams === 'string'
   273‚Üí				? this.#options.searchParams.replace(/^\?/, '')
   274‚Üí				: new URLSearchParams(Ky.#normalizeSearchParams(this.#options.searchParams) as unknown as SearchParamsInit).toString();
   275‚Üí			// eslint-disable-next-line unicorn/prevent-abbreviations
   276‚Üí			const searchParams = '?' + textSearchParams;
   277‚Üí			const url = this.request.url.replace(/(?:\?.*?)?(?=#|$)/, searchParams);
   278‚Üí
   279‚Üí			// Recreate request with the updated URL. We already have all options in this.#options, including duplex.
   280‚Üí			this.request = new globalThis.Request(url, this.#options as RequestInit);
   281‚Üí		}
   282‚Üí
   283‚Üí		// If `onUploadProgress` is passed, it uses the stream API internally
   284‚Üí		if (this.#options.onUploadProgress) {
   285‚Üí			if (typeof this.#options.onUploadProgress !== 'function') {
   286‚Üí				throw new TypeError('The `onUploadProgress` option must be a function');
   287‚Üí			}
   288‚Üí
   289‚Üí			if (!supportsRequestStreams) {
   290‚Üí				throw new Error('Request streams are not supported in your environment. The `duplex` option for `Request` is not available.');
   291‚Üí			}
   292‚Üí
   293‚Üí			this.request = this.#wrapRequestWithUploadProgress(this.request, this.#options.body ?? undefined);
   294‚Üí		}
   295‚Üí	}
   296‚Üí
   297‚Üí	#calculateDelay(): number {
   298‚Üí		const retryDelay = this.#options.retry.delay(this.#retryCount);
   299‚Üí
   300‚Üí		let jitteredDelay = retryDelay;
   301‚Üí		if (this.#options.retry.jitter === true) {
   302‚Üí			jitteredDelay = Math.random() * retryDelay;
   303‚Üí		} else if (typeof this.#options.retry.jitter === 'function') {
   304‚Üí			jitteredDelay = this.#options.retry.jitter(retryDelay);
   305‚Üí
   306‚Üí			if (!Number.isFinite(jitteredDelay) || jitteredDelay < 0) {
   307‚Üí				jitteredDelay = retryDelay;
   308‚Üí			}
   309‚Üí		}
   310‚Üí
   311‚Üí		// Handle undefined backoffLimit by treating it as no limit (Infinity)
   312‚Üí		const backoffLimit = this.#options.retry.backoffLimit ?? Number.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
   313‚Üí		return Math.min(backoffLimit, jitteredDelay);
   314‚Üí	}
   315‚Üí
   316‚Üí	async #calculateRetryDelay(error: unknown) {
   317‚Üí		this.#retryCount++;
   318‚Üí
   319‚Üí		if (this.#retryCount > this.#options.retry.limit) {
   320‚Üí			throw error;
   321‚Üí		}
   322‚Üí
   323‚Üí		// Wrap non-Error throws to ensure consistent error handling
   324‚Üí		const errorObject = error instanceof Error ? error : new NonError(error);
   325‚Üí
   326‚Üí		// Handle forced retry from afterResponse hook - skip method check and shouldRetry
   327‚Üí		if (errorObject instanceof ForceRetryError) {
   328‚Üí			return errorObject.customDelay ?? this.#calculateDelay();
   329‚Üí		}
   330‚Üí
   331‚Üí		// Check if method is retriable for non-forced retries
   332‚Üí		if (!this.#options.retry.methods.includes(this.request.method.toLowerCase())) {
   333‚Üí			throw error;
   334‚Üí		}
   335‚Üí
   336‚Üí		// User-provided shouldRetry function takes precedence over all other checks
   337‚Üí		if (this.#options.retry.shouldRetry !== undefined) {
   338‚Üí			const result = await this.#options.retry.shouldRetry({error: errorObject, retryCount: this.#retryCount});
   339‚Üí
   340‚Üí			// Strict boolean checking - only exact true/false are handled specially
   341‚Üí			if (result === false) {
   342‚Üí				throw error;
   343‚Üí			}
   344‚Üí
   345‚Üí			if (result === true) {
   346‚Üí				// Force retry - skip all other validation and return delay
   347‚Üí				return this.#calculateDelay();
   348‚Üí			}
   349‚Üí
   350‚Üí			// If undefined or any other value, fall through to default behavior
   351‚Üí		}
   352‚Üí
   353‚Üí		// Default timeout behavior
   354‚Üí		if (isTimeoutError(error) && !this.#options.retry.retryOnTimeout) {
   355‚Üí			throw error;
   356‚Üí		}
   357‚Üí
   358‚Üí		if (isHTTPError(error)) {
   359‚Üí			if (!this.#options.retry.statusCodes.includes(error.response.status)) {
   360‚Üí				throw error;
   361‚Üí			}
   362‚Üí
   363‚Üí			const retryAfter = error.response.headers.get('Retry-After')
   364‚Üí				?? error.response.headers.get('RateLimit-Reset')
   365‚Üí				?? error.response.headers.get('X-RateLimit-Retry-After') // Symfony-based services
   366‚Üí				?? error.response.headers.get('X-RateLimit-Reset') // GitHub
   367‚Üí				?? error.response.headers.get('X-Rate-Limit-Reset'); // Twitter
   368‚Üí			if (retryAfter && this.#options.retry.afterStatusCodes.includes(error.response.status)) {
   369‚Üí				let after = Number(retryAfter) * 1000;
   370‚Üí				if (Number.isNaN(after)) {
   371‚Üí					after = Date.parse(retryAfter) - Date.now();
   372‚Üí				} else if (after >= Date.parse('2024-01-01')) {
   373‚Üí					// A large number is treated as a timestamp (fixed threshold protects against clock skew)
   374‚Üí					after -= Date.now();
   375‚Üí				}
   376‚Üí
   377‚Üí				const max = this.#options.retry.maxRetryAfter ?? after;
   378‚Üí				// Don't apply jitter when server provides explicit retry timing
   379‚Üí				return after < max ? after : max;
   380‚Üí			}
   381‚Üí
   382‚Üí			if (error.response.status === 413) {
   383‚Üí				throw error;
   384‚Üí			}
   385‚Üí		}
   386‚Üí
   387‚Üí		return this.#calculateDelay();
   388‚Üí	}
   389‚Üí
   390‚Üí	#decorateResponse(response: Response): Response {
   391‚Üí		if (this.#options.parseJson) {
   392‚Üí			response.json = async () => this.#options.parseJson!(await response.text());
   393‚Üí		}
   394‚Üí
   395‚Üí		return response;
   396‚Üí	}
   397‚Üí
   398‚Üí	#cancelBody(body: ReadableStream | undefined): void {
   399‚Üí		if (!body) {
   400‚Üí			return;
   401‚Üí		}
   402‚Üí
   403‚Üí		// Ignore cancellation failures from already-locked or already-consumed streams.
   404‚Üí		void body.cancel().catch(() => undefined);
   405‚Üí	}
   406‚Üí
   407‚Üí	#cancelResponseBody(response: Response): void {
   408‚Üí		// Ignore cancellation failures from already-locked or already-consumed streams.
   409‚Üí		this.#cancelBody(response.body ?? undefined);
   410‚Üí	}
   411‚Üí
   412‚Üí	async #retry<T extends (...arguments_: any) => Promise<any>>(function_: T): Promise<ReturnType<T> | Response | void> {
   413‚Üí		try {
   414‚Üí			return await function_();
   415‚Üí		} catch (error) {
   416‚Üí			const ms = Math.min(await this.#calculateRetryDelay(error), maxSafeTimeout);
   417‚Üí			if (this.#retryCount < 1) {
   418‚Üí				throw error;
   419‚Üí			}
   420‚Üí
   421‚Üí			// Only use user-provided signal for delay, not our internal abortController
   422‚Üí			await delay(ms, this.#userProvidedAbortSignal ? {signal: this.#userProvidedAbortSignal} : {});
   423‚Üí
   424‚Üí			// Apply custom request from forced retry before beforeRetry hooks
   425‚Üí			// Ensure the custom request has the correct managed signal for timeouts and user aborts
   426‚Üí			if (error instanceof ForceRetryError && error.customRequest) {
   427‚Üí				const managedRequest = this.#options.signal
   428‚Üí					? new globalThis.Request(error.customRequest, {signal: this.#options.signal})
   429‚Üí					: new globalThis.Request(error.customRequest);
   430‚Üí
   431‚Üí				this.#assignRequest(managedRequest);
   432‚Üí			}
   433‚Üí
   434‚Üí			for (const hook of this.#options.hooks.beforeRetry) {
   435‚Üí				// eslint-disable-next-line no-await-in-loop
   436‚Üí				const hookResult = await hook({
   437‚Üí					request: this.request,
   438‚Üí					options: this.#getNormalizedOptions(),
   439‚Üí					error: error as Error,
   440‚Üí					retryCount: this.#retryCount,
   441‚Üí				});
   442‚Üí
   443‚Üí				if (hookResult instanceof globalThis.Request) {
   444‚Üí					this.#assignRequest(hookResult);
   445‚Üí					break;
   446‚Üí				}
   447‚Üí
   448‚Üí				// If a Response is returned, use it and skip the retry
   449‚Üí				if (hookResult instanceof globalThis.Response) {
   450‚Üí					return hookResult;
   451‚Üí				}
   452‚Üí
   453‚Üí				// If `stop` is returned from the hook, the retry process is stopped
   454‚Üí				if (hookResult === stop) {
